WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:20.959
Alright, and next up we have Dr. Sydeaka Watson.

00:00:20.959 --> 00:00:27.360
So perhaps as I get set up here, I can add to my resume that Max opened for me.

00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:36.520
So now I'm kind of a big deal, I guess.

00:00:36.520 --> 00:00:43.880
Okay, so good afternoon.

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:45.720
So my name is Sydeaka Watson.

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:51.119
I am a senior data scientist at a consulting firm called Illicit Insights.

00:00:51.119 --> 00:00:56.279
Most of our projects at Illicit are in the customer analytics and employee analytics

00:00:56.279 --> 00:01:01.360
space, and I'd be happy to chat more about some of those projects after this session.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:05.720
But this presentation is about a fun little side project that I've been working on.

00:01:05.720 --> 00:01:12.279
So I've listed my speaker affiliation here, Corolasi Data Insights.

00:01:12.279 --> 00:01:17.680
So title, Neural Networks for Longitudinal Data Analysis.

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:19.879
First let's start with the definition.

00:01:19.879 --> 00:01:25.519
So longitudinal data are recorded on the same units at multiple points in time.

00:01:25.519 --> 00:01:29.400
And so as an example, you could think about a clinical trial where you might have a patient

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:34.040
observed over multiple time points, maybe every three months, every six months or something.

00:01:34.040 --> 00:01:39.160
They come in and you take their vital signs, you weigh them, you take blood or tissue samples,

00:01:39.160 --> 00:01:43.440
and then maybe you record some biomarkers at each of the different time points.

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:45.480
So that's a healthcare example.

00:01:45.480 --> 00:01:50.160
Another example could come from retail where maybe you'd observe a customer's behaviors

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:56.320
or characteristics every month, or perhaps you're analyzing user behavior, so maybe you're

00:01:56.320 --> 00:02:00.800
at Facebook or Twitter, and you're looking at how the users behave or interact with the

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:02.160
platform every day.

00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:05.440
So there are lots of other examples.

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:11.119
In those applications, we're looking at people over time, but we could also have a longitudinal

00:02:11.119 --> 00:02:17.080
data set that stores information about buildings or objects, pets, anything really, whatever

00:02:17.080 --> 00:02:20.520
it is, where again, we're looking at the same thing over multiple time points.

00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:26.119
And they don't have to be, but usually the time points are evenly spaced, so say we're

00:02:26.119 --> 00:02:30.360
making observations every day or every month, and then the units don't necessarily have

00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:32.000
to have the same number of observations.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.520
So thinking back to that clinical trial example, some patients might come in only twice, and

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:39.520
then some patients might come in 10 times.

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:44.839
And you can think of each unit as having a matrix of data where the variables are observed

00:02:44.839 --> 00:02:50.880
or across the top of the matrix, and the time points are in the rows.

00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:58.639
Sean Lehman has a baseball database that is a fantastic example of longitudinal data collection.

00:02:58.639 --> 00:03:03.000
His data set has information about players in various roles and positions going back

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:09.559
to about 1871, and these data are available in the R package called Lehman, so when you

00:03:09.559 --> 00:03:12.919
install the package, you'll automatically get access to all of those data sets.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:20.080
But you could also visit his website and download those SCSVs from his website.

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:25.720
And when we load the tables, we get information about how well the players performed, how

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:30.639
well their teams performed as a group, whether they won any awards, whether they switched

00:03:30.639 --> 00:03:33.800
teams, all sorts of great information about the players.

00:03:33.800 --> 00:03:39.320
And for baseball hitters in particular, the batting statistics table captures all of the

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:44.679
usual performance metrics that are commonly reported on how well they were hitting.

00:03:44.679 --> 00:03:49.240
In particular, there are three primary baseball outcomes that make up what's called the slash

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:50.520
line.

00:03:50.520 --> 00:03:54.960
And these include the batting average, the on-base percentage and the slugging percentage.

00:03:54.960 --> 00:03:58.039
And these are usually reported as decimal numbers that are rounded to three decimal

00:03:58.039 --> 00:04:03.880
places with slashes in between them in that particular order.

00:04:03.919 --> 00:04:09.639
So let's suppose that we are particularly interested in three baseball players, and

00:04:09.639 --> 00:04:15.279
we know a lot of information about them over the past three seasons, but we'd like to know

00:04:15.279 --> 00:04:19.339
or predict how they're going to perform in the following season.

00:04:19.339 --> 00:04:22.600
So can we do that?

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:27.959
The first player in our collection of three players is Willie Mays, and again, we're just

00:04:27.959 --> 00:04:32.839
a spit's throw away from Black History Month, so I wanted to make sure I highlighted a high-performing

00:04:32.839 --> 00:04:35.000
African-American player.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:42.320
So Willie Mays, he had this incredible season in 1965, and in his slash line, both his on-base

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:47.959
percentage and his slugging percentage led the league, so he's just this powerhouse of

00:04:47.959 --> 00:04:48.959
a player, right?

00:04:48.959 --> 00:04:52.239
And in particular, 1965 was a good year for him.

00:04:52.239 --> 00:04:54.720
The second player is Greg Nettles.

00:04:54.720 --> 00:05:02.799
He in 1986 was playing his 20th season as a 41-year-old, which is really old for a player,

00:05:02.799 --> 00:05:13.600
but for a non-pitching player, I'm almost 40, so it's very young for other situations.

00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:17.239
And so his performance in 1986 was okay, right?

00:05:17.239 --> 00:05:19.720
So he's an example of a moderate player.

00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:26.959
And then we finally have Chris Davis, who had a terrible season in 2018.

00:05:26.959 --> 00:05:30.239
I'm sure maybe some of the baseball fans probably know a lot about him.

00:05:30.239 --> 00:05:38.320
He signed this massive $161 million contract and has been just vastly underperforming that.

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:42.559
And that year in particular, like I said, was a terrible year.

00:05:42.559 --> 00:05:47.940
So the question is, now that we have these three players in mind with varying performance,

00:05:47.940 --> 00:05:53.799
with their actual slash lines shown below, we'd like to somehow build a model that can

00:05:53.799 --> 00:05:56.559
predict these outcomes.

00:05:56.559 --> 00:06:01.519
Now for this type of scenario, we have three key modeling considerations.

00:06:01.519 --> 00:06:07.920
First, we know that there is a very strong correlation between past performance and future

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:09.239
performance.

00:06:09.239 --> 00:06:14.420
So data from one year to the next are highly correlated, and so we should have some sort

00:06:14.420 --> 00:06:22.160
of smart way to encode these temporal dependencies and exploit them if possible.

00:06:22.160 --> 00:06:25.359
Next we'd like to avoid—Max left, right?

00:06:25.359 --> 00:06:31.559
We'd like to avoid feature engineering over the different time periods.

00:06:31.559 --> 00:06:36.559
And so if you may have been dealing with this type of scenario in the past, maybe if you

00:06:36.559 --> 00:06:40.839
had data over multiple time points, you might say, OK, let me aggregate somehow over the

00:06:40.839 --> 00:06:45.480
different time points how many runs they had or look at some percentage from one period

00:06:45.480 --> 00:06:47.399
to the next or something like that.

00:06:47.399 --> 00:06:50.839
And then we might also have to manually encode some of the interactions between some of the

00:06:50.839 --> 00:06:51.839
variables.

00:06:51.839 --> 00:06:56.040
So obviously we're limited by time and our own imaginations, right?

00:06:56.040 --> 00:06:59.160
So there's almost an infinite number of ways that you could do that.

00:06:59.160 --> 00:07:05.820
And so we'd like to, if possible, allow the algorithm to come up with those types of transformations.

00:07:05.820 --> 00:07:12.920
And then finally, we would like this model to flexibly accommodate different types of

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:14.959
model outputs.

00:07:14.959 --> 00:07:18.079
We might want to predict more than one outcome at a time.

00:07:18.079 --> 00:07:23.559
So such as in our example where we want to predict the three numbers in the slash line.

00:07:23.559 --> 00:07:27.600
And normally in a regression, you would have three separate models, right, where you individually

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:31.040
predict those three outcomes.

00:07:31.040 --> 00:07:35.440
And then so each of those individual models are learning separate patterns that are predictive

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:36.440
of each of those outcomes.

00:07:36.440 --> 00:07:41.640
But maybe you want to have one model—maybe it's easier to maintain—that looks at individual

00:07:41.640 --> 00:07:47.079
patterns that can come together and simultaneously predict all of those outcomes.

00:07:47.079 --> 00:07:50.600
And maybe we also want to think about predicting over multiple time points.

00:07:50.600 --> 00:07:54.399
So maybe saying for those three players, could we predict how they performed over the next

00:07:54.399 --> 00:07:56.200
two or three seasons, right?

00:07:56.200 --> 00:07:59.000
So that's a lot to ask.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:03.079
Is there a modeling framework that can do all of that?

00:08:03.079 --> 00:08:07.959
Okay, so recurrent neural network models to the rescue.

00:08:07.959 --> 00:08:14.079
Those for people who have seen those before, you may have been aware that those naturally

00:08:14.079 --> 00:08:15.880
accommodate temporal dependencies.

00:08:15.880 --> 00:08:20.519
You've probably seen them before in different types of sequential data analyses such as

00:08:20.519 --> 00:08:23.480
written text or audio.

00:08:23.480 --> 00:08:27.600
There are some variants such as long short-term memory and gated recurrent units that can

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:33.359
regulate the flow of information through the network, in particular looking at data from

00:08:33.359 --> 00:08:35.039
one period to the next.

00:08:35.039 --> 00:08:43.239
So this slide shows an example of how information would flow through such a network for our

00:08:43.640 --> 00:08:48.599
incredible season, 1965 season for our high-performing player Willie Mays.

00:08:48.599 --> 00:08:55.559
And we see that he has the same attributes, age, games, number of hits, number of runs,

00:08:55.559 --> 00:09:04.119
etc., recorded with different values for each of these years in 1962, 1963, and 1964.

00:09:04.119 --> 00:09:10.280
And so the model is learning all of these season-to-season patterns over all the players

00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:15.640
that are predictive of these three outcomes in the slash line.

00:09:15.640 --> 00:09:23.679
To prepare the data, we must break each player's record into these rolling four-season windows.

00:09:23.679 --> 00:09:27.760
And so what that includes is the three seasons, remember, that we're using for prediction.

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:30.559
So those will be the input years of data.

00:09:30.559 --> 00:09:33.719
And then we've got the one season in the future, right?

00:09:33.719 --> 00:09:38.520
So one of the things that was an issue, of course, because players are not active every

00:09:38.520 --> 00:09:42.719
single year, is that if they were inactive for a particular season, we have to do some

00:09:42.719 --> 00:09:43.719
padding.

00:09:43.719 --> 00:09:46.280
And so there are some utilities in R that were helpful for that.

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:49.479
We have to pad the series to accommodate the skipped years.

00:09:49.479 --> 00:09:55.679
But for example, for Willie Mays, we could think about predicting 1962.

00:09:55.679 --> 00:10:02.799
So we're using the data from 59, 60, and 61, and using that to predict his 62 performance.

00:10:02.799 --> 00:10:05.080
And he was also active in 63.

00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:12.719
So we can slide that window to the right and have 60, 60, and 62 predicting 63.

00:10:12.719 --> 00:10:17.719
And we can do it again to predict 64, and slide it over one more time to predict 65.

00:10:17.719 --> 00:10:21.679
Now, this, of course, means that our data samples are not independent.

00:10:21.679 --> 00:10:26.520
And this is OK for now, because we're focusing primarily on the predictions that we're getting

00:10:26.520 --> 00:10:29.159
from the model at the moment.

00:10:29.159 --> 00:10:34.479
But there are some other aspects of this model where we will have to address this dependence

00:10:34.479 --> 00:10:35.960
issue head on.

00:10:35.960 --> 00:10:39.919
And so I'll revisit that a little later in the talk.

00:10:39.919 --> 00:10:43.919
I focused on data collected between 1916 and 2018.

00:10:43.919 --> 00:10:45.760
And I only looked at the players' first stint.

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:50.239
So I didn't consider what happened after they were traded to another team.

00:10:50.239 --> 00:10:54.479
And this was really just more of because of the way that the data was collected, it was

00:10:54.479 --> 00:10:57.559
actually reporting performance on each individual stint.

00:10:57.559 --> 00:11:01.400
I could have also aggregated across the different time points if I was doing this for real.

00:11:01.400 --> 00:11:03.760
But again, this was just an illustration.

00:11:04.039 --> 00:11:07.559
I only looked at players that had at least four consecutive seasons.

00:11:07.559 --> 00:11:11.640
And think about the way that I'm constructing these rolling windows.

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:16.719
So a player that has a longer career has more rolling windows, right?

00:11:16.719 --> 00:11:19.280
I'm sliding that window over a longer period of time.

00:11:19.280 --> 00:11:23.219
So that player will have more points in the data set.

00:11:23.219 --> 00:11:28.400
So to limit their influence, I downsampled players that had longer careers.

00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:33.840
And then to focus on hitters, I required the player to have at least 85 plate appearances.

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:40.080
Now another issue is that, so we also want to avoid data leakage.

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:45.200
And so think about the fact that we randomly are splitting the data into training and testing

00:11:45.200 --> 00:11:48.080
and validation sets.

00:11:48.080 --> 00:11:52.840
It's possible to have the same player represented in training and testing and validation if

00:11:52.840 --> 00:11:54.200
we're not careful, right?

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:59.039
And so in order to avoid that, one thing we could do is to just randomly split on the

00:11:59.039 --> 00:12:00.039
players.

00:12:00.039 --> 00:12:04.679
So you have the training players, the validation players, the testing players, and then you

00:12:04.679 --> 00:12:10.679
can compute the rolling windows for those individual players all across the data splits.

00:12:10.679 --> 00:12:16.200
As a benchmark, I fit an ordinary least squares regression model where the seasons, the three

00:12:16.200 --> 00:12:19.679
seasons of player data are represented in Y format.

00:12:19.679 --> 00:12:24.599
So if we had 100 features, that means we've got 300 columns of data.

00:12:24.599 --> 00:12:27.080
And 100 for each time period.

00:12:27.080 --> 00:12:28.760
I didn't do any manual feature engineering.

00:12:28.760 --> 00:12:32.840
Remember, that was one of the things I said in the beginning that I was trying to avoid.

00:12:32.840 --> 00:12:39.559
And I just used the data as it was, aside from doing some normalization to the 01 scale

00:12:39.559 --> 00:12:41.599
for the attributes and features.

00:12:41.599 --> 00:12:44.840
And I did that for the neural network approach as well.

00:12:44.840 --> 00:12:49.520
For the neural network approach, I tried different models that included one or more gated

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:55.599
recurrent unit layers and then one or more fully connected dense layers with tons of

00:12:55.599 --> 00:12:59.559
hyperparameter values tuned over the grid.

00:12:59.559 --> 00:13:03.159
And then I represented the model in two ways.

00:13:03.159 --> 00:13:09.039
The first approach was to look at three single outcome models where each model was just predicting

00:13:09.039 --> 00:13:11.200
a single metric in the slash line.

00:13:11.200 --> 00:13:15.400
And then I also looked at a multi-outcome model where I'm simultaneously predicting

00:13:15.400 --> 00:13:16.400
all three metrics.

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:23.400
It isn't on the slide, again, but I mentioned that normalization to the 01 scale.

00:13:23.400 --> 00:13:26.799
And so Max's talk just before this one was timely.

00:13:26.799 --> 00:13:31.840
Again, just thinking about model tuning and how important that is in machine learning

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:33.640
and neural networks in particular.

00:13:33.640 --> 00:13:39.640
So you're probably aware that these models involve a lot of parameters that must be tuned.

00:13:40.200 --> 00:13:47.400
A single run of this kind of model can take, you know, many minutes or hours or days sometimes.

00:13:47.400 --> 00:13:52.840
And so to cut down on the computational time, I used free services from Google Colab.

00:13:52.840 --> 00:13:56.400
They allow you to use a GPU for free.

00:13:56.400 --> 00:13:57.400
Within reason, obviously.

00:13:57.400 --> 00:14:01.320
I think they put some limits of up to 12 hours of modeling.

00:14:01.320 --> 00:14:02.559
But that was completely free.

00:14:02.559 --> 00:14:04.940
So that was helpful here.

00:14:04.940 --> 00:14:07.599
Especially for projects where you're just kind of playing around with something.

00:14:07.599 --> 00:14:11.679
So you'd want to probably use something like AWS, you know, the GPU if you're working on

00:14:11.679 --> 00:14:14.960
a real project.

00:14:14.960 --> 00:14:20.719
My GitHub repository has a complete minimal example showing how you could potentially

00:14:20.719 --> 00:14:23.520
implement this type of model in R.

00:14:23.520 --> 00:14:27.479
The version that I'm showing doesn't include all of the data joins and filtering and data

00:14:27.479 --> 00:14:31.799
transformations that were specific to the baseball example.

00:14:31.799 --> 00:14:36.159
So if you run this, you won't see the results that I'm going to share on the next few slides.

00:14:36.159 --> 00:14:41.119
But I did it this way because I wanted to keep this example simple enough so that you

00:14:41.119 --> 00:14:46.239
could think of this as a template that you could modify for your purposes and use it

00:14:46.239 --> 00:14:48.919
as inspiration for your projects.

00:14:48.919 --> 00:14:49.919
Okay.

00:14:49.919 --> 00:14:52.400
So after all of that, how did we do?

00:14:52.400 --> 00:14:53.400
Right?

00:14:53.400 --> 00:14:54.520
In our three modeling approaches.

00:14:54.520 --> 00:14:59.880
The first graph that I'm going to show here shows the performance in the ordinary least

00:14:59.880 --> 00:15:03.359
squares regression model on our held out test set.

00:15:03.359 --> 00:15:08.359
And so for each outcome in the slash line, I'm plotting the predicted values against

00:15:08.359 --> 00:15:10.200
the actual values.

00:15:10.200 --> 00:15:15.080
And this dash line is a reference that shows where the actuals match the predicted, which

00:15:15.080 --> 00:15:19.359
is where we want a majority of our points to lie in a great prediction model.

00:15:19.359 --> 00:15:22.599
And as we can see, this is not a great prediction model.

00:15:22.599 --> 00:15:23.599
Right?

00:15:23.599 --> 00:15:24.599
It's terrible.

00:15:24.599 --> 00:15:25.599
Okay.

00:15:25.599 --> 00:15:30.119
And our three selected players' performances are shown in the colored stars.

00:15:30.119 --> 00:15:31.599
I don't know if you can see those.

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:36.479
But I chose red for terrible, yellow for moderate, and green for great.

00:15:36.479 --> 00:15:40.559
So again, it doesn't seem to be doing a good job of predicting the outcomes for any of

00:15:40.559 --> 00:15:41.559
them.

00:15:41.559 --> 00:15:48.840
Next, we see the performance of the best gradient-boosted machine regression model that we observed

00:15:48.840 --> 00:15:51.760
over the grid of hyperparameter values.

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:56.159
And you might have noticed from this slide compared to the previous one that the mean

00:15:56.159 --> 00:15:58.599
square error is lower.

00:15:58.599 --> 00:16:04.039
But it doesn't appear to be doing a much better job of predicting compared to even

00:16:04.039 --> 00:16:05.479
ordinarily squares.

00:16:05.479 --> 00:16:07.440
And so I have a couple theories about that.

00:16:07.440 --> 00:16:12.679
One is that we, again, there's the data from time point one, time point two, time point

00:16:12.679 --> 00:16:18.559
three, where it's not actually clear to the data, to the model, that there's some temporal

00:16:18.559 --> 00:16:19.559
dependency here.

00:16:19.559 --> 00:16:21.719
So that's actually not being captured there.

00:16:21.719 --> 00:16:22.719
So that's one thing.

00:16:22.719 --> 00:16:27.359
And the second is that there might be some types of data transformations or interactions

00:16:27.359 --> 00:16:32.000
or something that if we were to manually encode some of those things, maybe the model

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.599
might be better.

00:16:34.599 --> 00:16:36.239
Okay.

00:16:36.239 --> 00:16:39.599
And then finally, we have our neural network model fits.

00:16:39.599 --> 00:16:44.880
And notice how a majority of the points lie close to the line, often on the line.

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:50.719
And for our three selected players, the model was able to capture Willie May's excellent

00:16:50.719 --> 00:16:56.119
performance, Greg Nettle's okay performance, and Chris Davis's terrible performance in

00:16:56.119 --> 00:16:57.799
those three specific years.

00:16:57.799 --> 00:17:04.560
So yeah, I can quit my job and work in fantasy baseball and make a lot of money, right?

00:17:04.560 --> 00:17:05.560
No.

00:17:05.560 --> 00:17:07.880
So obviously, this was done more for illustration purposes.

00:17:07.880 --> 00:17:11.640
If I was really trying to deploy this, of course, I'd have to do a lot of other types

00:17:11.640 --> 00:17:12.640
of validation.

00:17:12.640 --> 00:17:18.040
But again, this is illustrating the point that these types of models are useful for

00:17:18.040 --> 00:17:21.079
longitudinal data analysis.

00:17:21.079 --> 00:17:24.400
There are some issues that I haven't talked about in this short talk that we might explore

00:17:24.400 --> 00:17:25.400
in a future session.

00:17:25.680 --> 00:17:30.479
I mentioned earlier that the neural network enables you to predict multiple time steps

00:17:30.479 --> 00:17:31.760
in the future.

00:17:31.760 --> 00:17:34.880
But I haven't talked about how you would do that.

00:17:34.880 --> 00:17:38.800
Really that it just involves changing the shape of the output layer.

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:42.359
And so that's just making some you'd also have to make some adjustments to the loss

00:17:42.359 --> 00:17:47.599
function, potentially, if you were wanting to, for example, emphasize that you want the

00:17:47.599 --> 00:17:52.119
model to perform better in earlier time points compared to later time points or later versus

00:17:52.119 --> 00:17:53.319
earlier or something like that.

00:17:53.359 --> 00:17:55.959
So those are those are things that you could do.

00:17:55.959 --> 00:18:00.160
And then the elephant in the room, again, is that I have not talked about prediction

00:18:00.160 --> 00:18:01.160
intervals.

00:18:01.160 --> 00:18:04.079
So we talked about point estimates, estimating that one number.

00:18:04.079 --> 00:18:09.640
But getting some sort of estimate of some range of value, some reasonable range of values

00:18:09.640 --> 00:18:15.599
that that actual value could lie within is something that we would have to spend a little

00:18:15.599 --> 00:18:17.040
bit more time thinking about.

00:18:17.040 --> 00:18:21.439
Remember, we're talking about that correlation structure from before.

00:18:21.439 --> 00:18:27.520
There's this nagging dependence issue that we've introduced by producing these rolling

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:28.520
windows.

00:18:28.520 --> 00:18:31.479
So that's something we would certainly have to work out.

